metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #665
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: CA Panico RGB #1
metadata.description:
Another tribute to Stephen Wolfram and his cellular automata, that's a reworking of my previous CA Panico collection.

In this version the RGB basic colors reign supreme, every single color is set by a cellular automata formula, giving life to interesting and particular textures and patterns.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: Not so iso #29
metadata.description:
Isometric and Glitch, order and chaos, two apparently incompatible art forms, two completely different worlds, two types of art that I love.
This collection aims to combine these two styles without distorting them.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: CA Monti #95
metadata.description:
As a sequel of previous collection CA Vista but with a completely different approach, CA Monti intends to explore landscape generation through the use of Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: Context-Free Wind #40
metadata.description:
Context-Free Wind is a poetry generator and visualizer created by Ross Goodwin (https://rossgoodwin.com) in vanilla JavaScript without the use of any framework or external libraries, excluding code required by fxhash. The generator uses a custom context-free grammar algorithm and word lists assembled by the creator to produce (...admittedly, fairly strange...) sentences.

These sentences are then blown aloft by a procedural "wind" -- based on the algorithm Goodwin first explored in the following Dweet:
https://www.dwitter.net/d/23927

metadata.name: Artifice #391
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (3000‚Ää√ó‚Ää3600)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 9000‚Ää√ó10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Barrage #87
metadata.description:
Barrage (/b…ôÀàr…ë í/ french for dam) is a project that proposes a narrative by invoking a game of radical composition. The program traverses a texture, searching for gaps in depth. When it identifies deep areas, it will draw lines, and when they are high, it will write text. The texture will then define the width and height of the letters and the direction of the lines. 

Randomly for each edition, the text will be written vertically or horizontally, but it will always be repeated, becoming a kind of incantation, a statement that is repeated endlessly while awaiting the intervention of a higher power, but also like an instruction in code that will be executed a certain number of times or until a condition is met.

Textures and texts hybridize, the text is no longer flat but in motion, altered by a Perlin noise that renders it illegible in places and, at other times, enlarged, dominating the rest of the composition. Like an elocution, the text now has a rhythm, its acceleration and its hollows: it comes alive.

___

Click on the edition to generate an image (PNG) or a vector (SVG).

You are free to plot your edition by your own and if you want a signed edition you can use the great feature "reedemable" of fxhash to order a small (A4) or a large (A3) plotter drawing of your edition.

Project setup with thi-ng/tpl-umbrella-fxhash
Using thi.ng/umbrella, nclslbrn/plotter-writer and simplex-noise packages.

2024 Nicolas Lebrun

metadata.name: Reading a book #691
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Self, Ego #123
metadata.description:
The third and final installment of the Self trilogy.

Ego is defined as: the one of the three divisions of the psyche in psychoanalytic theory that serves as the organized conscious mediator between the person and reality especially by functioning both in the perception of and adaptation to reality.

Please see attached fx(text) article or go to https://ty-vek.art/self-trilogy for more on concept/mechanics/etc. It‚Äôs a bit of long read, but worth it.

This is an fx(params) project and you will be able to choose exactly what your iteration will look like. For more details on why this is a params project and how to approach that, check out the article.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

All projects are written in vanilla Javascript, composed as SVG and then rendered to a 2d canvas.

There might be slight differences in rendering from browser to browser. This is expected as they might translate the SVG slightly differently. Let's call Chromium renderings canonical. They also render faster there and we love that.

Press "S" to save a PNG.
Press "V" to save a SVG. (Chromium browsers render these pretty well.)

By default, these will render at 2400 x 3200 pixels. This is at density 1.

To render at a larger resolution you can append ‚Äú&d=2‚Äù to the end of the url. This will double the resolution. You can also use 3 or 4 or whatever your browser can handle. Safari tends to have problems with this, so stick with Chromium based browsers (Chrome, Edge, Brave, etc.)

If you want to render as a square image, so it is optimized for ummm.. your pfp or something, you can append ‚Äú&sq=t‚Äù to the url.

If you want to get rid of grain, just append ‚Äú&g=n‚Äù

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

metadata.name: Constellation Of Happiness #131
metadata.description:
Constellation Of Happiness is a collaborative art project between NFT artists Kato Trofimova and Andrew Erickson.

Feeling happy is tough this year but it'll be much easier when you get your own constellation of happiness! Using expressionistic code art, Constellation Of Happiness channels the purest festive emotions a person can experience, for example, when tasting champagne bubbles or seeing and touching confetti. All these are turned into beautiful constellations of happiness using the aesthetics of star maps and carefully brought to your NFT collection.

2022

Kato Trofimova (Latvia) is an illustrator, visual artist, and creative director known for her love of minimalistic shapes and bright palettes. In her art, Kato questions boundaries between styles and stays optimistic no matter what.

Andrew Erickson (Switzerland) is a generative artist experimenting with various abstract styles. Be it delicate monochromatic line art or colorful gradient minimalism, Andrew is very good at coding any kind of digital beauty.

Hit 'p' in live mode to save a 9922‚Ää√ó‚Ää14032px PNG (for printing up to A0)
Hit 's' in live mode to save a plottable SVG

10% of proceeds go to support Processing.org

metadata.name: As the Wind Blows #222
metadata.description:
As the leaves slowly fall...floating through the winds of winter. A fresh scent wafts through the air, and with it comes youthful memories of hopping on the school bus, waving back at your parents, and staring out the classroom window.

Dreams and the memories of life are never motionless‚Äîjust as the wind never stops blowing.


Controls:
Double-click to resize the Sketch to your window.
Press S to save a copy of the sketch.

Written in p5js, showcasing the blessings of nature.
Created by Alex and Andrew Mitchell in Autumn 2023
